cember 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"nb\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{Soccerway}}\n* {{NFT player}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{CAF Most Promising Talent of the Year}}\n{{MLS Goal of the Year}}\n{{2014 MLS Best XI}}\n{{Chinese FA Cup top scorers}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Nigeria squads\n| bg = #008751\n| fg = White\n| bordercolor = \n| list1 = \n{{Nigeria squad 2006 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Nigeria squad 2008 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Nigeria squad 2010 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Nigeria squad 2010 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martins, Obafemi}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lagos]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Yoruba sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Nigerian footballers]]\n[[Category:Nigeria international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:2006 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2008 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2010 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2010 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Italy]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in China]]\n[[Category:Reggio Audace F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Newcastle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:VfL Wolfsburg players]]\n[[Category:FC Rubin Kazan players]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Levante UD footballers]]\n[[Category:Seattle Sounders FC players]]\n[[Category:Shanghai Shenhua F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Bundesliga players]]\n[[Category:Russian Premier League players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:Chinese Super League players]]\n[[Category:Designated Players (MLS)]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:Nigerian expatriate sportspeople in China]]\n[[Category:F.C. Ebedei players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian footballer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Obafemi Martins\n| image               = Martins Llevant.jpg\n| image_size          = 180\n| caption             = Martins playing for [[Levante UD|Levante]] in 2012\n| fullname            = Obafemi Akinwunmi Martins<ref>{{cite web |url=http://actas.rfef.es/actas/RFEF_CmpActa1?cod_primaria=1000144&CodActa=19388 |title=Acta del Partido celebrado el 02 de marzo de 2013, en Valencia |trans-title=Minutes of the Match held on 2 March 2013, in Valencia |publisher=Royal Spanish Football Federation |accessdate=16 June 2019 |language=Spanish}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1984|10|28|df=y}}<ref name=interstats/>\n| birth_place         = [[Lagos]], Nigeria\n| height              = 1.70 m<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/22/85/78/fwc_2010_squadlists.pdf#page=22 |format=PDF |title=FIFA World Cup South Africa 2010 List of Players |publisher=FIFA |page=22 |date=4 June 2010 |accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref>\n| currentclub         = \n| clubnumber          = \n| position            = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1         = 1999\u20132000\n| youthclubs1         = [[F.C. Ebedei|Ebedei]]\n| youthyears2         = 2000\u20132001\n| youthclubs2         = [[A.C. Reggiana 1919|Reggiana]]\n| youthyears3         = 2001\u20132002\n| youthclubs3         = [[Inter Milan]]\n| years1              = 2000\u20132001\n| clubs1              = [[A.C. Reggiana 1919|Reggiana]]\n| caps1 = 2  | goals1 = 0\n| years2              = 2001\u20132006\n| clubs2              = [[Inter Milan]]<ref name=interstats>{{cite web |url=http://www.inter.it/en/archivio_giocatore/G0745 |title=Obafemi Martins |work=Archive |publisher=Inter Milan |accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref>\n| caps2 = 88 | goals2 = 28\n| years3              = 2006\u20132009\n| clubs3              = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n| caps3 = 88 | goals3 = 28\n| years4              = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs4              = [[VfL Wolfsburg]]\n| caps4 = 16 | goals4 = 6\n| years5              = 2010\u20132012\n| clubs5              = [[FC Rubin Kazan|Rubin Kazan]]\n| caps5 = 20 | goals5 = 3\n| years6              = 2011\n| clubs6              = \u2192 [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] (loan)\n| caps6 = 4  | goals6 = 0\n| years7              = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs7              = [[Levante UD|Levante]]\n| caps7 = 21 | goals7 = 7\n| years8              = 2013\u20132015\n| clubs8              = [[Seattle Sounders FC]]\n| caps8 = 72 | goals8 = 40\n| years9              = 2016\u20132018\n| clubs9              = [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]]\n| caps9 = 40  | goals9 = 19<!-- league matches and goals only -->\n| nationalyears1      = 2004\u20132015\n| nationalteam1       = [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 42 | nationalgoals1 = 19\n| club-update         = 07:44, 3 April 2018 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 19 November 2015\n}}\n'''Obafemi Akinwunmi Martins''' (born 28 October 1984) is a Nigerian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. He is known for his speed on the ball. After leaving Nigeria for Italy at age 16, he has since played for a number of [[List of top-division football clubs in UEFA countries|top-division clubs around Europe]]. He began his senior career in 2002 at [[Serie A]] club [[Inter Milan]], before moving to [[Premier League]] club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in 2006, and then to [[Bundesliga]] club [[VfL Wolfsburg]] in 2009. Having joined [[Russian Premier League]] side Rubin Kazan in July 2010, they [[loan (sports)|loaned]] him to [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in January 2011.\n\nIn club football, Martins has won the Serie A title, the [[Coppa Italia|Italian Cup]] (twice), and the [[Supercoppa Italiana|Italian Super Cup]], all with Inter. With Birmingham he scored the winning goal in the [[2011 Football League Cup Final]]. He has played [[European football]] with Inter, Newcastle and Wolfsburg, winning the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]] with Newcastle. His highest scoring league seasons so far have seen him score 11 goals in the [[2004\u201305 Serie A]], and 17 in both the [[2006\u201307 FA Premier League|2006\u201307 Premier League]] and [[2014 Major League Soccer season|2014 MLS]]. In international football, Martins has been in the Nigerian squad for the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] in [[2006 Africa Cup of Nations|2006]], [[2008 Africa Cup of Nations|2008]] and [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations|2010]], and for the [[FIFA World Cup]] in [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]]. He played for [[Seattle Sounders FC]] of Major League Soccer from 2013 to 2015, scoring 40 goals, before moving on to China.\n\nMartins had two brothers who also played football professionally. His elder brother, [[Oladipupo Martins]], played for [[A.C. Reggiana 1919|Reggiana]], [[FK Partizan|Partizan]] and [[Innsbrucker AC|Innsbruck]] before retiring from football in 2009 due to heart problems. He died on 8 August 2011 of a suspected heart attack in Lagos, Nigeria.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://socqer.com/questions/839/how-did-nigerias-obafemi-martins-brother-die/ | title = How Did Nigeria's Obafemi Martins' Brother Die? | publisher = Socqer.com | date = 10 August 2011 | accessdate =3 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vanguardngr.com/2011/08/martins%E2%80%99-brother-dies-of-heart-problem/ | title = Martins' Brother Dies of Heart Problem | publisher = Vanguard | date = 9 August 2011 | accessdate =3 August 2012}}</ref> Martins' younger brother is John Ronan Martins. The name \"Obafemi\" translates literally to \"the king loves me\" in the [[Yoruba language]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nigerian.name/w/index.php?title=Obafemi | title = Meaning of Obafemi | publisher = Nigerian.name | accessdate =3 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nMartins joined the local football club [[F.C. Ebedei]], having been scouted by manager [[Churchill Oliseh]] while playing on the streets of his hometown. After a year with the club, [[Serie C]] side [[A.C. Reggiana 1919|A.C. Reggiana]] made a move for the player. After a three-month trial, Martins and fellow Ebedei teammate [[Stephen Makinwa]] signed youth contracts with the club in 2000. His first season in Italy saw Martins break into the first team squad, and later in the year [[Serie A]] sides [[Perugia]] and [[Inter Milan]] made offers for the [[forward (football)|forward]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/obafemi-martins-leap-of-faith-from-lagos-to-newcastle-462901.html|title=Obafemi Martins: Leap of faith from Lagos to Newcastle|date=25 August 2007|work=The Independent|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5v400bnd5?url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/obafemi-martins-leap-of-faith-from-lagos-to-newcastle-462901.html|archivedate=18 December 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Inter Milan===\n[[File:17 aprile al meazza (9689231) (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Martins (right) with Inter Milan in 2005]]\nMartins was signed by Inter Milan in 2001 for a \u20ac750,000 [[transfer fee]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://110.inter.it/en/obafemi-martins-en/martins-testo3eng/|title=Mister Oba Oba|publisher=inter.it|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> and in his first season he scored 23 goals for the youth team, helping them to win the [[Campionato Nazionale Primavera]] in 2001\u201302 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2002/febbraio/12/festa_tutta_dell_Inter_ga_0_0202121158.shtml|title=La festa \u00e8 tutta dell' Inter|trans-title=The celebration is all for Inter|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=12 February 2002|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> His form for the youth side led to his first-team league debut the following season, starting in a match against [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] on 22 December 2002 which was won by Inter 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calcio.com/cronaca_partita/serie-a-2002-2003-parma-fc-inter/|title=Parma 1:2 Inter|publisher=Calcio.com|language=Italian|date=22 December 2002|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nMartins didn't become a regular member of the first team squad until the 2002\u201303 season. During this season he was given his first [[UEFA Champions League]] appearance by manager [[H\u00e9ctor C\u00faper]], entering as a substitute against his future employers, Newcastle United, at [[St James' Park]]. He scored his first Champions League goal in a match against [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen]] to secure Inter's place in the quarter finals; footage of his celebratory somersaults were subsequently used by UEFA to advertise the following season's competition. He scored again in the semi-final match against Inter's arch-rivals [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], but couldn't prevent the club losing out on [[away goals]] to the competition's eventual winners.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2002/matches/round=1637/match=1038266/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Inter passage paved by Martins|publisher=UEFA.com|date=19 March 2003|accessdate=3 August 2012}}</ref> In the championship, he scored once in four appearances.<ref name=interstats/>\n\nMartins signed a long-term contract with Inter Milan in 2005 which ran until 2010 and was worth around \u20ac2.5&nbsp;million annually.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11860/2358387/Martins-signs-new-Inter-deal|title=Martins signs new Inter deal|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|author=Nadia Carminati|date=1 December 2005|accessdate=4 March 2007}}</ref> By scoring in the 3\u20131 win at [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]] in the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group G|2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League group stage]], Martins become the first ever teenage to score in three consecutive Champions League seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/sports/football/kylian-mbappe-equals-obafemi-martins-in-uefa-champions-league-id8872594.html|title=Kylian Mbappe equals Obafemi Martins record|publisher=Pulse.ng|author=Tosin Abayomi|date=19 September 2018|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> He was also protagonist in team's successful run in [[2004\u201305 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], scoring six goals, including a hat-trick against [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calcio.com/cronaca_partita/coppa-italia-2004-2005-achtelfinale-bologna-fc-inter/|title=Bologna 1:3 Inter|publisher=Calcio.com|language=Italian|date=12 January 2005|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> as the tournament ended in conquest.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/58655/tbt-2005-coppa-italia-triumph|title=#TBT: 2005 Coppa Italia triumph|publisher=inter.it|date=15 June 2017|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref> Martins amassed 22 goals in 45 matches across all competitions, setting a new personal best; his good form for Inter earned him a spot in Nigeria's [[2006 Africa Cup of Nations]] squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jan/16/africannationscup2006.africannationscup1|title=Group D|publisher=The Guardian|author=Paul Doyle|date=16 January 2006|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nAlthough he had some success with Inter, scoring 28 goals for the club in 88 league games as well as 11 goals in European competitions, he was sold in August 2006. This was due to Inter bringing in two new strikers; first Argentinian [[Hern\u00e1n Crespo]] was brought in on [[loan (sports)|loan]] from [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and then the Swede [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]] was bought by Inter from [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].<ref name=AsksToLeaveInter>{{cite news | date=7 August 2006 | url= http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11860_2385460,00.htm | title = Martins asks to leave | publisher = [[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=4 March 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\n[[File:Oba Martins.JPG|170px|thumb|Martins warming up before a match]]\nAfter Martins submitted a transfer request,<ref name=AsksToLeaveInter/> [[Premier League]] club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] completed a deal with Inter for the striker on 24 August 2006 for \u20ac15&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.nufc.co.uk/staticFiles/ea/3d/0,,10278~81386,00.pdf | title = Newcastle FC 2006 Annual Report | publisher = Newcastle FC | accessdate = 3 August 2012 | format = PDF | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121002101544/http://www.nufc.co.uk/staticFiles/ea/3d/0%2C%2C10278~81386%2C00.pdf | archivedate = 2 October 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Martins signed a five-year deal. He was paraded in front of the [[Geordie]] fans before their UEFA cup tie against [[FK Ventspils]], and inherited the club's cherished number 9 shirt, vacated after the retirement of the club-record goalscorer [[Alan Shearer]] in April.\n\nMartins made his Premier League debut on 27 August, in the 2\u20130 defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], in which he was stretchered off with a knee injury. It turned out that Martins suffered a severe dead leg and internal bleeding. His unremarkable first few appearances for Newcastle caused manager [[Glenn Roeder]] to speak out in his defence.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/5334604.stm | title=Be patient with Martins \u2013 Roeder | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | date = 11 September 2006 | accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Butt and Martins.jpg|thumb|left|170px|Martins with Newcastle teammate [[Nicky Butt]] in 2007]]\n\nHowever, on 17 September, Martins scored his first goal for Newcastle. It was the second goal in a 2\u20130 victory over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] at [[Boleyn Ground|Upton Park]], and from there his goalscoring form began to improve steadily.\n\nReports in January 2007 suggested that [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] were considering making an offer for Martins' services after his impressive form. These reports were later rubbished by Martins himself,<ref>{{cite news | date=11 January 2007 | url=http://home.skysports.com/list.aspx?hlid=440846&CPID=8&clid=4&lid=&title=Martins+slams+Chelsea+links | title=Martins slams Chelsea links | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070114000959/http://home.skysports.com/list.aspx?hlid=440846&CPID=8&clid=4&lid=&title=Martins+slams+Chelsea+links |archivedate=14 January 2007 |first=Graeme |last=Bailey}}</ref> and Roeder stated that although he was interested in signing a Chelsea player, he would not allow Martins to leave Newcastle.<ref>{{cite news | date=28 January 2007 | url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11668/2403733/ | title=Roeder admits Blues enquiry | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] |first=James |last=Pearson |accessdate=4 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 January, in a 2\u20133 away win against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], Martins' 20-yard shot rocketed into the net. This strike was clocked by [[Sky Sports]] at a speed of 84&nbsp;mph (135&nbsp;km/h), making it unofficially the ninth hardest shot ever recorded in football according to the ''Guardian'' website.<ref>{{Cite news | date=14 February 2007 | url=http://football.guardian.co.uk/theknowledge/story/0,,2012031,00.html | title=The hardest recorded shot in football \u2013 ever | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | accessdate=4 March 2007 | location=London | first1=James | last1=Dart | first2 =  Paolo | last2 = Bandini}}</ref> This was his tenth goal for Newcastle. Martins ended his first season on Tyneside with 17 goals in 46 games.\n\n[[File:Obafemi Martins.png|thumb|right|170px|Martins at a pre-season training camp with Newcastle in 2007]]\n\nHis second season was somewhat mixed. With new manager [[Sam Allardyce]] preferring to play [[Michael Owen]] and [[Mark Viduka]] up front, Martins found himself being used as an impact substitute for the first half of the season. Despite this he managed to score consistently, and when Allardyce was sacked and [[Kevin Keegan]] was appointed, Martins found himself being used as part of a three pronged attack along with Owen and Viduka. Martins scored fewer goals in his second season with Newcastle, mainly due to him no longer being the focal point of all their attacks as he was in his first season with them, as well as his season being interrupted with the African Cup of Nations participation with Nigeria in December.\n\nMartins scored six goals in 12 league games during the first half of the 2008\u201309 season before a torn hamstring ruled him out for several games.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/football/3993745.Martins_missing_for_Magpies_against_Spurs/|title=Martins missing for Magpies against Spurs|date=21 December 2008|accessdate=29 December 2008|newspaper=The Northern Echo | first = Paul | last = Fraser}}</ref> It was confirmed on 7 January 2009, that Martins would undergo hernia surgery in Germany the next Monday. He was operated on by renowned specialist Dr. Ulrike Muschaweck. He did make it back in time for the last two games of the season, scoring in a relegation six-pointer derby against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]. However, he could not stop Newcastle being relegated to the Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://soccernet-assets.espn.go.com/news/story?id=607546&sec=england&cc=5739 | title = Toon striker Martins forced into hernia op | publisher = ESPN Soccernet | date = 7 January 2009| accessdate = 7 January 2009}}</ref> He initially reiterated his desire to stay and help the club return to the [[Premier League]] for the 2009\u201310 season, but he eventually left for [[VfL Wolfsburg]]. His last game was in a preseason friendly against [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]], which Newcastle lost 6\u20131.\n\nDuring his three-year spell on Tyneside, Martins amassed 35 goals in all competitions from 104 games.\n\n===VfL Wolfsburg===\nOn 29 July 2009, Newcastle accepted a \u00a39&nbsp;million bid from [[Bundesliga]] champions [[VfL Wolfsburg]], the transfer was confirmed on 31 July with Martins signing a four-year contract.<ref>{{cite news | date=31 July 2009 | url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_5464649,00.html | title=Wolfsburg seal Martins deal | publisher=Sky Sports | accessdate=31 July 2009}}</ref> For his debut, Martins came on as a second-half substitute against [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]] at the [[Rhein Energie Stadion]], with his team deadlocked at 1\u20131. He helped in the buildup to the second goal and capped off his first appearance in the Bundesliga with a well-taken goal after dribbling past two onrushing defenders and then coolly finishing from six yards out, slotting the ball past the goalkeeper to the far post.\n\n===Rubin Kazan===\nOn 9 July 2010, Martins was sold for a reported \u20ac17&nbsp;million to reigning [[Russian Premier League]] champions [[FC Rubin Kazan|Rubin Kazan]]. He signed a three-year contract and told [[BBC Sport]]: \"I am joining a team of champions and I hope to bring my best to the club to make them even greater.\" Martins' agent, Nicola Walter, revealed that Rubin met all of the player's requirements and that manager [[Kurban Berdyev]] had a \"massive role\" for him to play, following the departure of striker [[Aleksandr Bukharov]]. Martins was able to make his debut with Rubin after 1 August, when the transfer window was opened. On 9 May 2012, Rubin Kazan won the Russian Cup giving Martins his first trophy in Russia.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/8806226.stm|title=Nigeria's Obafemi Martins signs for Russian champions|publisher=BBC Sport|date=9 July 2010 |first=Oluwashina|last=Okeleji|accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sports.ru/football/71707662.html|script-title=ru:\"\u0420\u0443\u0431\u0438\u043d\" \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043b \"\u0412\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0444\u0441\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0443\" \u0437\u0430 \u041e\u0431\u0430\u0444\u0435\u043c\u0438 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0430 16 \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0435\u0432\u0440\u043e, \u0441\u0440\u043e\u043a \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u2013 3 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430|publisher=sports.ru|date=9 July 2010|language=Russian | accessdate = 3 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Birmingham City====\n[[File:Martinsbirmingham2011.png|150px|thumb|Martins celebrating after the [[2011 Football League Cup Final]]]]\nFollowing the birth of his child, Martins requested a move to England to be nearer to his family.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://rubin-kazan.ru/en/news/club/1904.html |title=Martins will play in Birmingham City on loan |publisher=FC Rubin Kazan |date=28 January 2011 |accessdate=31 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202091726/http://rubin-kazan.ru/en/news/club/1904.html |archivedate=2 February 2011  }}</ref> On 31 January 2011, he joined Premier League club [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on loan until the end of the season,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bcfc.com/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~2279243,00.html |title=Blues complete Martins deal |publisher=Birmingham City F.C |accessdate=31 January 2011 |date=31 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110203034921/http://www.bcfc.com/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~2279243,00.html |archivedate=3 February 2011  }}</ref> with the option of a \u00a35&nbsp;million permanent deal in the summer of 2011.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.net/birmingham-sport/birmingham-city-fc/2011/02/01/birmingham-city-fend-off-major-bid-as-they-land-obafemi-martins-97319-28090412/ |title=Birmingham City fend off major bid as they land Obafemi Martins |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |accessdate=1 February 2011 |date=1 February 2011 | first = Colin | last = Tattum}}</ref> He made his debut, which had been delayed by the formalities of obtaining a working visa, in the starting eleven against [[Stoke City]] on 12 February; he played for 75 minutes as Birmingham won 1\u20130.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/9392077.stm |title=Nigeria's Obafemi Martins set for Birmingham City debut  |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 February 2011 |accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9391008.stm |title=Birmingham 1\u20130 Stoke |first=Les |last=Roopanarine |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 February 2011 |accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club, 17 minutes into the FA Cup fifth-round defeat of [[Sheffield Wednesday]], after a strong run.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/feb/21/birmingham-city-sheffield-wednesday-fa-cup |title=Birmingham cruise leaves Gary Megson lamenting woeful Wednesday |first=David |last=Lacey |newspaper=The Guardian |date=21 February 2011 |accessdate=21 February 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nMartins scored the winning goal in the [[2011 Football League Cup Final]] as Birmingham beat [[Arsenal F.C|Arsenal]] 2\u20131 at [[Wembley Stadium]], having been brought on as an 83rd-minute substitute.  With one minute remaining in normal time, there was a moment of confusion between Arsenal goalkeeper [[Wojciech Szcz\u0119sny]] and defender [[Laurent Koscielny]] as they attempted to deal with a headed knock down from Birmingham's [[Nikola \u017digi\u0107]]. Martins passed the resulting loose ball into the empty net from near the penalty spot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theglobalherald.com/football-arsenal-1-2-birmingham-carling-cup-final-2011-result/12195/|title=Football: Arsenal 1\u20132 Birmingham, Carling Cup Final 2011 Result|work=The Global Herald|date=27 February 2011|accessdate=27 February 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717000540/http://theglobalherald.com/football-arsenal-1-2-birmingham-carling-cup-final-2011-result/12195/|archivedate=17 July 2011}}</ref> Martins described it as \"the easiest goal I've ever scored in my career\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/886988/birmingham-city%27s-obafemi-martins-celebrates-%27easiest%27-goal?cc=5739 |title=Jubilant Martins celebrates victory |publisher=ESPN Soccernet |date=27 February 2011 |accessdate=28 February 2011}}</ref> After two more Premier League appearances, he spent several weeks out with an injury eventually diagnosed as a [[stress fracture]] of the left [[tibia]]. After surgery in late April, he faced a recovery period estimated at three to four months.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://world.bcfc.com/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~2349296,00.html |title=Oba out for the season |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=29 April 2011 |accessdate=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Levante===\n\n[[File:Obafemi Martins.jpg|thumb|left|Martins (pictured with Levante in 2012) is known for [[Goal celebration|celebrating a goal]] with a backflip]]\nOn 13 September 2012, Martins moved to [[Levante UD|Levante]] on a free transfer, signing a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.marca.com/2012/09/13/futbol/equipos/levante/1347523350.html |title=El Levante ya espera a Martins |publisher=Marca.com |accessdate=13 September 2012 |date=13 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Oluwashina |last=Okeleji |title=Nigeria's Martins completes Levante move |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19428314 |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) |date=14 September 2012 |accessdate=7 October 2012}}</ref> He made his league debut on 23 September 2012, where he scored his first goal, and the winning goal, in a 2\u20131 home win against [[Real Sociedad]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Martins marks debut with winner | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=348466&cc=5739 |work=ESPN Soccernet |publisher=Entertainment and Sports Programming Network (ESPN) |date=23 September 2012 |accessdate=7 October 2012}}</ref> Martins scored a brace for Levante in their 3\u20131 home victory over [[Granada CF|Granada]] on 28 October, sending his side into fourth place in the La Liga standings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/levante-3-1-granada-martins-double-puts-jims-men-fourth/ |title=Levante 3\u20131 Granada: Martins double puts JIM's men fourth |first=Heath |last=Chesters |website=Inside Spanish Football |date=28 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130127005517/http://www.insidespanishfootball.com/levante-3-1-granada-martins-double-puts-jims-men-fourth/ |archivedate=27 January 2013  }}</ref>\n\n===Seattle Sounders FC===\n[[File:Obafemi Martins at SeaTac Airport.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Martins at Seattle Tacoma International Airport upon arrival to [[Seattle Sounders FC]] in 2013]]\nOn 11 March 2013, it was announced that Martins signed with [[Major League Soccer|MLS]] club [[Seattle Sounders FC]] as a [[Designated Player]] after the club paid a $4&nbsp;million buyout clause in Martins' contract with Levante. The move concluded weeks of speculation of a possible Martins move to Seattle. Levante had been hesitant to lose Martins mid-season, and had threatened Sounders FC with a tampering lawsuit.<ref>{{cite web|last=Adewuyi|first=Lolade|title=Obafemi Martins signs for Seattle Sounders|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ng/news/4093/nigeria/2013/03/11/3784666/breaking-news-obafemi-martins-signs-for-seattle-sounders|publisher=GOAL.com|accessdate=11 March 2013|date=11 March 2013}}</ref> On 15 March 2013, the club announced that the signing was official.<ref>{{cite web |title = Sounders FC Signs Nigerian Striker Obafemi Martins |url = http://www.soundersfc.com/News/Articles/2013/03-March/Sounders-FC-Signs-Nigerian-Striker-Obafemi-Martins.aspx | date = 15 March 2013 | accessdate = 15 March 2013 | work = Seattle Sounders FC | publisher = Sounders FC Public Relations}}</ref> Martins scored his first goal for the club on 20 April 2013, performing his signature back-flip goal celebration.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mlssoccer.com/players/obafemi-martins | title = Obafemi Martins | publisher = mlssoccer.com | accessdate = 20 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 October 2014, Martins signed a new three-year contract extension with Seattle, nearly doubling his annual salary to more than $3 million.<ref name=\"MLS extension\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/major-league-soccer/story/2107886/seattle-sounders-give-obafemi-martins-new-deal-worth-$3-million-a-year-sources |title=Sounders give Obafemi Martins deal worth $3 million a year, sources say |work=ESPNFC |date=24 October 2014 |accessdate=26 October 2014 }}</ref> The following day, Martins provided an assist for [[Marco Pappa]]'s first goal as Seattle defeated the [[Los Angeles Galaxy|Galaxy]] 2\u20130 to win the [[Supporters' Shield]].<ref name=\"Seattle Times blog\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/soundersfc/2014/10/25/first-impressions-sounders-2-galaxy-0/ |title=First impressions: Sounders 2, Galaxy 0 |work=Seattle Times |date=25 October 2014 |accessdate=26 October 2014 }}</ref> The assist meant that Martins finished with 17 goals during the regular season, a club record, as well as notching 13 assists, a joint-club record held with [[Mauro Rosales]].<ref name=\"MLS extension\" /><ref name=\"Seattle Times blog\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soundersnation.com/2014/10/15/obafemi-martins-robbie-keane-race-mvp/ |title=Obafemi Martins, Robbie Keane Race For MVP |work=Sounders Nation |date=15 October 2014 |accessdate=26 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\nMartins had a very successful 2014 season with the Sounders, his second with the club, and was named as one of three [[Landon Donovan MVP Award|MLS MVP]] finalists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2014/11/20/robbie-keane-obafemi-martins-lee-nguyen-vie-mvp-mls-announces-awards-finalists | title=Robbie Keane, Obafemi Martins, Lee Nguyen vie for MVP as MLS announces 2014 awards finalists |date=20 November 2014 | accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> Martins was named to the [[MLS Best XI]] and the Sounders won every game in which he scored.<ref name=\"MLS reveals 2014 Best XI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2014/12/02/mls-reveals-2014-best-xi-headlined-landon-donovan-thierry-henry |title=MLS reveals 2014 Best XI| date=2 December 2014 | accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> He also won [[MLS Goal of the Year]] for a looping goal he shot from an extremely tight angle near the end line into the far netting over [[San Jose Earthquakes|Earthquakes]] keeper [[Jon Busch]].<ref name=\"mlssoccer.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/gotw/goty2014 |title=2014 Goal of the Year Winner: Obafemi Martins|accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Shanghai Shenhua===\nOn 18 February 2016, Martins was signed for [[Chinese Super League]] side [[Shanghai Greenland Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35573893 | title = Obafemi Martins leaves MLS for Chinese Super League | website = BBC Sport | date = 18 February 2016 | access-date = 21 February 2016}}</ref> On 15 May 2016, he scored his first goal with Shanghai as a late substitute in a 5\u20131 win over [[Guangzhou R&F]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.shanghaidaily.com/sports/soccer/Shenhua-punishes-RF-51/shdaily.shtml | title = Shenhua punishes R&F 5-1 | website = Shanghai Daily | date = 16 May 2016 | access-date = 21 May 2016}}</ref> Martins scored the only goal in the first leg of the [[2017 Chinese FA Cup]] final and scored a spectacular goal in the second. Although their opponents, [[Shanghai SIPG]], won the second leg 3\u20132, Shanghai Shenhua won the trophy on away goals.<ref name=2017CFACup>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42130472 |title=Nigeria's Obafemi Martins helps Shenhua win Chinese FA Cup |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 November 2017 |accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2018, Martins scored his first hat-trick for Shenhua in a 4\u20132 home win against [[Hebei China Fortune F.C.|Hebei China Fortune]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2018-03-31/doc-ifysunqz6308106.shtml|title=\u4e2d\u8d85-\u9a6c\u4e01\u65af\u6234\u5e3d\u74dc\u6797\u5efa\u529f \u7533\u82b14-2\u9006\u8f6c\u534e\u590f\u53d6\u8fde\u80dc|publisher=Sina Sport |date=31 March 2018 |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> However, he suffered a partial rupture of tendon of quadriceps femoris at his right knee in the fifth group stage match of [[2018 AFC Champions League]] against [[Kashima Antlers]] on 3 April 2018, which ruling him out for at least six months.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2018-04-04/doc-ifysuuya5308315.shtml|title=\u7533\u82b1\u516c\u5e03\u9a6c\u4e01\u65af\u4f24\u60c5:\u808c\u8171\u90e8\u5206\u65ad\u88c2 \u5eb7\u590d\u97006-7\u4e2a\u6708|publisher=Sina Sport |date=4 April 2018 |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> On 1 June 2018 it was announced that Martins had been waived from Shenhua.<ref>{{cite web | title = \u767b\u5df4\u5df4\u56de\u5f52\u7533\u82b1\u5728\u5373 \u9a6c\u4e01\u65af\u5df2\u89e3\u7ea6\u6ce8\u518c\u65e0\u969c\u788d  | url = http://sports.sina.com.cn/china/j/2018-06-01/doc-ihcikcew1900340.shtml | publisher = sina.com | date=1 June 2018 | access-date=25 October 2018 | language = zh}}</ref>\n\nHe suffered a torn hamstring in May 2019, and in November 2019 said that he was seeking a new club following his recovery from injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50360479|title=Obafemi Martins: Nigeria star not contemplating retirement yet| website = BBC Sport | date = 9 November 2019 | access-date = 11 November 2019 | first = Oluwashina  | last = Okeleji}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nMartins made his debut for Nigeria in 2004 at the age of 19 in the 2004 [[Unity Cup]] scoring the second goal, in the tri-nations Unity Cup tournament in London.<ref>{{Cite news | date=30 May 2004 | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/3762457.stm | title=Martins delighted with debut | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> He was a part of the Nigerian team that finished third in the [[2006 African Cup of Nations]]. Martins scored two goals in the competition, both coming against [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] in the first round.\n\nHis future for the national team has been placed in doubt on numerous occasions after separate incidents of controversy. In August 2006, the [[Nigeria Football Association|Nigerian FA]] (NFA) website had his date of birth down as 1 May 1978, which would have made him 28 years of age rather than 21. The NFA soon confirmed that it had been an administrative error and apologised for the confusion it had caused. However Martins threatened to quit playing for the national team after the blunder had initially put his move to Newcastle in doubt.<ref>{{Cite news | date=4 August 2006 | url=http://www.vanguardngr.com/articles/2002/sports/august05/04082005/sp104082005.html | title=NFA embarrasses Obafemi Martins, ridicules Nigeria | publisher= Vanguard | accessdate=4 March 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061031063329/http://www.vanguardngr.com/articles/2002/sports/august05/04082005/sp104082005.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 31 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 February 2007, Martins failed to turn up for the 4\u20131 friendly defeat against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]], despite being ordered to play. He later explained his absence was due to the fact he had travelled to Lagos to visit his sick mother.<ref>{{Cite news | date=7 February 2007 | url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/6339843.stm | title=Martins no-show for sick mother | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref>\nThe Nigerian caretaker coach [[Augustine Eguavoen]] was furious with Martins and threatened to ban him from the national team.<ref>{{cite news | date=9 February 2007 | url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/6345871.stm | title=Nigeria get tough on Martins | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=25 May 2011 | first=Oluwashina | last=Okeleji}}</ref> On 14 February 2007, Martins apologised for missing the game but said he believed his mother's health was more important. He also said that he would be available to play for Nigeria in the future.<ref>{{Cite news | date=14 February 2007 | url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/africa/6360583.stm | title=Martins sorry for Nigeria no-show | publisher=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=25 May 2011}}</ref> He made his return to the national side on 24 March 2007, playing the full match against [[Uganda national football team|Uganda]] in an [[African Cup of Nations]] Qualifying match and won.\n\nFollowing the end of Nigeria's [[2008 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] campaign, Nigeria faced Mexico in [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]] for a friendly match. Martins scored two goals in a 2\u20132 draw.\n\nOn 17 November 2007, Martins captained Nigeria for the first time, in a friendly match against Australia for his 19th appearance. On 12 November 2009 he scored a spectacular goal in the 83rd minute against [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]] in Nairobi, thus ensuring Nigeria's qualification for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]]. At the finals in South Africa, Martins played in just two games for a total of 71 minutes, without scoring.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/players/player=199817/index.html | title = 2010 FIFA World Cup\u2122 \u2013 Obafemi MARTINS | publisher = FIFA.com | accessdate =3 August 2012}}</ref> In the first group game, he came on as a 52nd-minute substitute for [[Victor Obinna]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249722/match=300061460/index.html | title = Argentina 1:0 (1:0) Nigeria | publisher = FIFA.com | date = 12 June 2010 | accessdate =3 August 2012}}</ref> In the third game he was used as a 57th-minute substitute for [[Nwankwo Kanu]].<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/matches/round=249722/match=300111115/index.html | title = Nigeria 2:2 (1:1) Korea Republic | publisher = FIFA.com | date = 22 June 2010 | accessdate =3 August 2012}}</ref> Nigeria exited the tournament bottom of [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group B|Group B]] with only one point.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/teams/team=43876/index.html | title = Nigeria | publisher = FIFA.com | accessdate =3 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\n[[File:Obafemi Martins defended by LA Galaxy.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Martins in action for Seattle in 2014]]\nA fast, diminutive, and agile left-footed striker, who is quick on the ball, Martins is primarily known for his outstanding pace, mobility, and athleticism as a footballer, as well as his striking power, and his strength, in spite of his small stature; he has also stood out for his acrobatic goal celebrations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2005/02/04/martins-scatti-gol-timidezza-le-mie-capriole.html|title=Martins, scatti gol e timidezza Le mie capriole per Mancini|trans-title=Martins, sprints goals and shyness My back-flips for Mancini|publisher=La Repubblica|author1=Andrea Sorrentino|language=Italian|date=4 February 2005|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2003/maggio/04/acrobazie_Martins_non_svegliano_Inter_co_5_030504023.shtml|title=Le acrobazie di Martins non svegliano l' Inter|trans-title=Martins's acrobatics don't wake Inter up|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|author1=Mario Gherarducci|language=Italian|date=4 May 2003|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMartins received his [[Permanent residence (United States)|U.S. green card]] in 2015 which qualifies him as a domestic player for MLS roster purposes.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.sounderatheart.com/2015/12/17/10454458/obafemi-martins-indeed-has-a-green-card | title = Obafemi Martins indeed has a green card | website = sounderatheart.com | date = 17 December 2015 | access-date = 27 December 2015 | first = Jeremiah | last = Oshan}}</ref>\n\nHe is married to Ghanaian-Italian Abigail Barwuah, sister of [[Mario Balotelli]]. The couple have one child named Kendrick, born in 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gossip.it/news/mario-balotelli-nipote-swag-news.html | title = Mario Balotelli non ha dubbi: 'Mio nipote \u00e8 swag'. Il calciatore innamorato del figlio di Abigail Barwuah e Obafemi Martins, Kendrick | language = it | website = gossip.it | date = 15 October 2015 | access-date = 7 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|3 April 2018}}.<ref name=\"Obafemi Martins\">{{cite web | title = Obafemi Martins | url = http://soccernet.espn.go.com/player/_/id/25785/obafemi-martins?cc=5739 | publisher = ESPN Soccernet | accessdate =25 May 2011}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Other<ref group=\"nb\">Includes other competitive competitions, including the [[Russian Super Cup]], the [[Supercoppa Italiana]], the [[MLS Cup playoffs]] and the [[Chinese FA Super Cup]].</ref>\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season\n! Club\n! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n! colspan=3 |Italy\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Coppa Italia]]\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|2000\u201301||[[A.C. Reggiana 1919|Reggiana]]||[[Lega Pro Prima Divisione|Serie C1]]||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 Inter Milan season|2001\u201302]]||rowspan=\"5\"|[[Inter Milan]]||rowspan=\"5\"|[[Serie A]]||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 Inter Milan season|2002\u201303]]||4||1||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||3\n|-\n|[[2003\u201304 Inter Milan season|2003\u201304]]||25||7||3||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||9||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||37||11\n|-\n|[[2004\u201305 Inter Milan season|2004\u201305]]||31||11||6||6||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||8||5||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||45||22\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 Inter Milan season|2005\u201306]]||28||9||6||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||9||2||1||0||44||13\n|-\n! colspan=3 |England\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[FA Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Other\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Newcastle United F.C. season|2006\u201307]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Premier League]]||33||11||2||0||2||0||9||6||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||46||17\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Newcastle United F.C. season|2007\u201308]]||31||9||0||0||2||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||33||10\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 Newcastle United F.C. season|2008\u201309]]||24||8||0||0||1||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||25||8\n|-\n! colspan=3 |Germany\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[DFB-Pokal]]\n! colspan=2 | [[DFB Ligapokal]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|